// engine-012-hierarchy-cascade — parent-rule cascade dispatch (§51.0.Q.2).
//
// Demonstrates the canonical "parent-rule cascade" worked example from
// SPEC §51.0.Q.2: when code inside a composite writes to either the inner
// OR the outer engine variable, the static-from-state knowledge follows
// the canonical §51.0.F rule per variable:
//
//   - Write to INNER variable (e.g. @playMode = .Battle): from-state is the
//     inner state-child the write originates from. Validated against the
//     INNER state-child's `rule=`.
//
//   - Write to OUTER variable (e.g. @appMode = .Paused) from inside the
//     composite: from-state is the COMPOSITE outer state-child. Validated
//     against the composite's `rule=`.
//
// No new dispatch mechanic — "cascade" is conceptual framing for which
// `rule=` contract governs which variable's writes from which scope. This
// gives nested engines the same compile-time discipline as flat engines
// without introducing a new keyword or runtime machinery.
//
// Temporal transitions (<onTimeout>, <onIdle>) are engine-specific per
// OQ-Harel-7 — a timer on the inner engine fires only while inner is
// active (requires outer to be in composite). Timers do NOT cascade
// across the inner/outer boundary.
//
// Per §51.0.Q.3, when a write inside a composite is rejected by the outer
// composite's `rule=`, the diagnostic message extends to name BOTH engines
// for clarity. (No new error code — extension of E-ENGINE-INVALID-TRANSITION
// message form.)
//
// v1 implementation state (2026-05-11):
//   - Parser + typer surface the parent-rule contract via existing §51.0.F
//     mechanic applied per-variable.
//   - The cascade-miss diagnostic message-extension is a typer follow-on.
//   - Inner-engine state-child bodies with rich markup are also Wave 4
//     follow-on — the body-parser currently attributes inner state-children
//     to the OUTER engine when they carry non-empty bodies. This sample
//     keeps inner state-children empty and surfaces the cascade-write
//     pattern via the OUTER composite body and via FILE-LEVEL handlers
//     (writes to @playMode at file scope hit the inner engine's variable
//     through the same rule= discipline once inner is active).

<program>
${
    type AppMode:enum  = { Title, Playing, Paused }
    type PlayMode:enum = { Exploring, Battle, Inventory }
}

<engine for=AppMode initial=.Title>
    <Title rule=.Playing></>

    <Playing rule=(.Title | .Paused)>
        // Composite body: nested engine + outer-scoped controls.
        // Writes to @appMode here are validated against `<Playing>`'s rule=:
        //   .Title and .Paused are legal targets; anything else fires
        //   E-ENGINE-INVALID-TRANSITION.
        <engine for=PlayMode initial=.Exploring>
            <Exploring rule=.Battle></>
            <Battle rule=.Exploring></>
            <Inventory></>
        </>

        <button onclick=${@appMode = AppMode.Paused}>Pause game</>
        <button onclick=${@appMode = AppMode.Title}>Quit</>
    </>

    <Paused rule=.Playing></>
</>

<div class="game">
    <h1>App: ${@appMode.variant}</>
    <p>Inner play-mode: ${@playMode.variant}</>
    <button onclick=${@appMode = AppMode.Playing}>Start</>

    // File-scope writes to the inner variable @playMode are validated
    // against whichever inner state-child is active per §51.0.F:
    //   .Exploring → .Battle    is legal
    //   .Battle    → .Exploring is legal
    // Anything else fires E-ENGINE-INVALID-TRANSITION at the write site.
    <button onclick=${@playMode = PlayMode.Battle}>Fight (Exploring → Battle)</>
    <button onclick=${@playMode = PlayMode.Exploring}>Flee (Battle → Exploring)</>
</div>
</program>
